Duel to the last blood: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will recommend how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
However, there are many reasons why you should get a self-contained reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
However, if hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
There are also the price and quality categories here.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the twenty crowns headphones of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the battery life that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but they don’t do it by mistake.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Alongside the primary functions, calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even surf.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle since no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, don’t count on them to last for more than a few hours.
If you still add us, from time to time, some calls, get at work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours with continuous functionality with a charge.
An additional problem exists when you download music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
The readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create themselves a media library sorted by the names of the performers, album name, genre, or user classification.
Some devices reproduce only the tree structure of the folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, pay particular attention to battery endurance, memory capacity, quality and the type of audio outputs, and clearly to ease of use.
If you need the music above all as a background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This is now possible, clearly on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats the mobile phone or the reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to them will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular ones, the majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their phones behind them.
For anyone who wants to listen to something, scour your pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, whether you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
Instead, the advantage of the readers is, in addition to others, the easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally colliding with the start-up of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even cheaper phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an interchangeable memory card slot (such as M2, microSD, etc.).
As far as the purchase of the respective card is concerned, you also fall within the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and also want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you should not spend more than 1100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, prefer the specialized phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area has made more way Sony Ericsson, which phones of the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the brands listed above provide you with the same service and the same price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, usually up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Possibly
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here – a virtual trader forcing traditional traders to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, noting that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's final steps in the field of regularising roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the clash.
Maybe it sounds absurd, but here we have three mobile networks and coverage that is well above 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (In fact, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that has led to a significant drop in prices, to which traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices resounded in Britain.
It has been shown, however, that the place for such operators is there and that they can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go very far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to conquer more than 100,000 customers and to become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the more restricted service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a group-target not little.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company who produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can say a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from a service point of view, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there ever will be an operator in the Czech Republic, Mobilking will not be.
"There is talk of expanding this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, press spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation with Mobile.cz.
Thus it indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitors are created.
For some time now it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunication.
And the sooner you do, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them," says Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have to be by the end of the year.
For now, however, around its creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now we don’t believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press section of Telef<0xC3><0xB2>nika O2 mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build.”
He adds: “A virtual operator is unlikely to appear on the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this point we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its 3G license requests.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities - with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when operators care about something they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which the virtual operator is not accepted.
Martina Kemrová commented: “The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been further enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and especially on his services.
However, the attitude of mobile operators is surprising because of the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, with respect to the whole problem, has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been attractive enough for traditional traders," Kristián Chalupa, from the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS external relations section, said in the answer to our question.
Such a formulated statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead of the office that has to defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “Overseas where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the lower prices for mobile services.”
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of gasoline for all gas stations is without a doubt the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
“The section has found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking for the telecoms regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s analysis of the relevant markets, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant necessarily.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators proceed in such an oddly similar way.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all traders they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps itself out of the whole affair.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the recently approved telecommunications law, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the improvement of the situation.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one looks
While without us noticing it remains the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually the companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company faces the operator as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of the cooperation with that company," Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
That is to say, they derive a profit from the activity of these companies and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators.
But that should be a strange minimum for <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another issue opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to it will not have to settle for the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the operators were born, the traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, at the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, it is precisely in these cases that the regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not the mobile operators but their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and he was joined by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw the whole case from one to the other like a boiling potato.
From our experience we can not get rid of the feeling that the unclearness of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw out the sponge.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will appear really soon with us, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain impassive to the refusal (discrimination) of the other concerned.
And maybe we'll stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
