The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss candidates’ positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California studies and senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School.”
Really attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “Afro-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s educational plan specifically advocates, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in classroom languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The school’s students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 math state exam.
An equally surprising 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert-level test on the art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s preferred one.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills, and an "no apologies" attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach for English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We had fantastic success with a student just coming from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you wouldn’t be able to pinpoint what it was.”
"It works," he remarked, "for us it works."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model to replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools with English students?
The results achieved by the school make the answer to that question very easy, but the education policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and its own continued support for bilingual education prevents us from predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the topic trivial when he said that people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "you need to make sure that your children are able to speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than despise or trivialize them.
