In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extended theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, Harlem Renaissance's most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described – and which makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a separate place.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that “knowing so little about us, she doesn’t know what she’s missing.”
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, was called for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grabbing and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shade of oaks of the sometimes disdained, sometimes award-winning rural culture of the South born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's imagination really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida into a setting of black history and human drama.
Low as a heap in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Outside the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it the way it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls Hurston immortalizes by quoting men who sing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moving to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston stepped into the city, he usually arrived without warning in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts of dignified clothing today.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others smiled.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, she added, swinging on her chair on the patio at the back above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big commemorative ceremonies, and no big conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a Hurston biography published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane highway.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had brought an end to the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the front door of the community.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on the side," says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say that desegregation of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
“Black children were used to being hugged — I remember this — hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
“You didn’t hug your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there’s a cultural divide there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston’s plaqueless tomb and began to struggle for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed Robert E. Hemenway biography of Hurston hit the shelves of bookstores, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had turned on the spotlight again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its project on the road.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway, brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the city’s image of itself.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical record in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a re-paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a back road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It’s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for the history of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
Permission requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, for some things — such as the murals on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a plump teacher, with a fondness for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing her entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, not better, not worse and proud, creative, great worker, foolish and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Many people, if they've just come in here, will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
