"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract the character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no steering wheels, no old-fashioned clothes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or the woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this objective, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day more and more," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed “on the road” are “artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and to capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are inner.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a slab camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects the conception of flamenco typical of Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not the dance, the singing or the playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, capable of conquering the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, figure in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, know them and be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters that sometimes you don’t even know or that give you just a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to materialize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the gallery El Fotómata, at number 20 of via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next October 16.
