Recurrent drivers of alcoholism will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, install in their car the system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of intoxication or if you do not blow into the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Securitate dell'Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for driving intoxicated then return to drive the car.
The alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents starting the car if the driver does not blow, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce up to 65% of the infractions committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to put a stop to these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, no doubt, the necessary reform for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
The device, however, is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some commercial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the PSOE in which it proposes to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
