Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
This is a benign sleep disorder called sleep apnea.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadicly (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nocturnal enuresis (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a vent to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign disorder so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, instead, is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the child before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more comfortably.
Once sleepwalkers appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and so he is resting.
Remember that if you look very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will not get anything, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he is saying but not to see what he is dreaming of to say it, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell your child that you might ask him or her questions overnight to learn his or her secrets.
Not even a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, do not worry, it is nothing serious, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
