The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the trust of the public, seriously shaken by the blood-infected scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such drama and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
As Judge Krever delayed writing a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
As a result of the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
“Thanks to continued efforts to improve blood safety and field research over the years, we have regained the public’s confidence,” he said, adding that by the beginning of 2008, about 94 percent of Quebec’s population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could get a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for some years now, it has been proven that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to that in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to a duration of less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to detect them has thus decreased significantly.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is detected.
I believe that today one can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health, says the head of the direction of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We need to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary continued, noting that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“The needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors.
However, all healthy people over the age of 18 who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is widespread, they will be rejected for a period equal to one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to retain them and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is hard to find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for serious burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec, which runs the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago when our 1,000th cord blood sample was placed in the bank and we expect to collect more than 1,000 each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of drawing cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
