Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, managing vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, squatter publishing house with the intention of launching a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation complaint, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to hers.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial sum of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these odd-numbered struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to speak out again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada usually take place with the exchange of opinions and not with batons.
It would therefore have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a “public” debate when his contempt for that same audience is evident?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word indicates only the well-paid lawyers and not all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This public is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the light of what many perceive as a sort of gag (seeking the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum telling them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, Barrack Gold’s lawsuit constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss about uncomfortable topics to the richest companies in the world, under penalty of multiple lawsuits, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the university world, as is public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to curb abusive lawsuits.
Operation - Rescue for Wall Street - Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, yesterday finally reached an agreement on the largest bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has been weighing on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of inspection on the remuneration paid to the managers of the protected companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Senator Judd Gregg at the negotiating table announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Every decision has been made in a way that safeguards the economy and the American people from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“This is the crucial point: If we hadn’t acted in this way, invaluable heartbreak and upheaval would have spilled over into the daily lives of Americans,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
United later in the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential elections were rather favorable to the agreement, without however avoiding expressing their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular one that will allow owners to keep their homes and that inherent in the salaries for managers of companies covered by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
