The Psychology of Excess Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are inclined to spend more, to overvalue the merchandise.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have been able to uncover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science men do not want to stay behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price too.
The research tried to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win some money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body striated under the cerebral cortex intensively goes into operation when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this survey, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
In addition to this, another group has been promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of $15.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was underlined, while for the other the loss.
Proving the neurologists' hypothesis members of the group that played "against the loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "win".
“These findings are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These in fact until now explained the phenomena that can be found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to a hundred thousand, of whom only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leakage, saliva).
For travelers it is useful to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and the whites of the eyes, the stools become light and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens deviously destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
In the world today the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth turning to the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, the religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci’s Hermelin painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a reassuring effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this period of time received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel “safe,” as if “someone took care of” them and “they were reassured and pervaded by peace.”
Looking at the religious-themed image they accounted for 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work before them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
"We have to look for an image towards which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains if the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to the believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
