When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said: “He would like if Google could answer questions like ‘what do I do tomorrow?’ or ‘what would be the right job for me?’, but the software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their internet searches exactly the words they are looking for are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search initiated two years ago, for example, users can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our preferences declared and registered previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - they ask users concerned about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the reactions of Internet users are caused by the fright felt by the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the guilt, by the fear of punishment, by the desire for freedom or even by the rebellion to power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has been perhaps the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made possible the identification of pedophiles from the page of the Orkut community maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights instead sighed with relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even later you can not force Google with any point of the constitution to provide any information requested secretly by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped off nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain individual user search lists and the entire list of two-month-old web pages and keywords.)
The judgment of Google is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data slap Google because they believe that this is how their intimate sphere and privacy is affected by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion due to multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users in many countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies precisely one of the keywords repeated most often in recent years, the web 2.0.
The Web 2.0 speaks only of collaboration, of intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can insert them in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, he can also write blogs on which his latest photo galleries automatically appear stored on Flickr or on Picasa.
Meanwhile we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common tour of friends, comes to know easily with whom she spent the night her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because she wrote a sincere opinion on the top of the company: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has now been completely reconsidered.
Those who live an online life make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do so (starting for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time not voluntarily leaving traces).
There are not a few people who do not deliberately register on community pages to not be found, Google's online applications, from text processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not tied to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far.
The public is not even secretly waiting for the moment when Google will pull out its claws.
Currently, the company with its 156 billion dollars worth is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords / AdSense advertising space threatens the revenue of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time cause serious harm not only to Microsoft but also to many software development companies.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the company summit for example has completely rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the fee of the company's kindergarten, has considered too expensive the repeated catering to the daily pleasure of employees, all this however diminishes the fact that in 2006 Google has bowed the head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter the interests.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is certain, however, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world at one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines from Google will take on such proportions that our company will soon find itself in front of the American Health Supreme Court, others are afraid of the system.
The fact that Google is building a genetic data base can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the Scroogled tale by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
