Intelligent machine imitates the flight of the hornet
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if not to imitate the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, those of the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets gave Nissan engineers an initial strategic cue on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic minicar with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks very much like our protective shield – explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's sight, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of bee sight.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent to avoid the accident.
This maneuver of avoidance, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it weren’t so, the robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what one bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation can not go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steerability of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to the bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high-energy-density lithium polymer batteries, which means they last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot needs to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvring data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of an immediate collision avoidance technology that, according to Nissan, can be installed on production vehicles within 10 years.
Further application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding obstacles on the road leads to destination.
