Járóka, according to the press office of the parliamentary group Fidesz PE, recalled, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, that the Roma are expelled from the labor market primarily because of their low schooling.
"The majority of young Roma do not have a middle-level qualification and as a result of low-quality elementary education only a small number of them can achieve a higher qualification."
Mr Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in enforcing human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economies of EU member states.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these links in the wider context between Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner a Roma start school, the more their chances of becoming a productive member of the labor market increase; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation’s budget.
“The right of Roma to European citizenship must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools,” said Lívia Járóka.
According to the deputy, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary to accelerate the processes of desegregation of schools and for this it is of fundamental importance to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
