MP3 Players Under Accusation, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
The European Commission cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSSERI) published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day while holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"A clear risk emerges from the scientific evidence and we need to react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise caused by them.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to these sources of noise.
You can greatly limit this damage by using solutions such as reducing noise exposure levels and duration.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment if they listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week exceed the limits currently in force regarding the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent loss of hearing after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of the users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
