Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times yesterday confirmed this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, which has become powerfully alive with the vow I said at the beginning.
But this is just one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps foreshadows or already reveals: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the United States and in Europe, the crisis seems to be working as an accelerator of phenomena in incubation for a long time and in the new climate they solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, strong links with foreign countries, but which first of all see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, involved to a very large extent.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or has little to say: the clear evidence is given by the European Union which, as usual, divides between different interests and between different state strategies, fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all disbursement of funds: since when you get to the straits are only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to get things right.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is moreover in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal increasingly with those very little immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So that those who are sovereign possess certainly several more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune of living in a place without harvests, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which foreshadows a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, proved to be so inadequate and full of shadows.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufficiency, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
In other words, there seems to be a growing belief, in large sections of the population, that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites that have so far risen, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, that they have made their time and are increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political arrangements, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and last times, from the victory of the Americans to the rise of the conservative in Austria-Bavaria, to the collapse of the Laburists.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape today in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, increasing, potentially agitating.
In the face of all this, to speak of a “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
Keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
