Students victims of expensive rents up to 900 euros for a room
The housing market for university students is not in crisis.
According to the latest Sunia survey, the tenants’ union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now assumed very serious characters to the point of excluding entire groups of young people from the right to study for the very high overall costs that the families of origin should support - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has so distorted the market that it triggers a process of generalized increase also for the residents".
In most cases, the lease offers also contain a series of violations: free, unregistered, no fee limit, sub-rents linked.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are needed that, through the revision of the taxation, can calm prices.
Looking at the detail of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room it goes from a minimum of 650 (Black Bands area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) about 600 euros are asked for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values only slightly lower (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You save only if you move in peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed you need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a greater weight in the city economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of rents to non-EU students is more frequent, as in Perugia, there is finally a further anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% of the fee charged to foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multi-sale and the consequent death by consumption of the mono-sale in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Disappearing are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and which told the poetry of a provincial theater and the nostalgia for a way of life.
The figures provided by Anec, the main traders' association, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and the biggest ones are the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the ANEC, "it is useful that new structures are built but the survival of existing ones should be guaranteed, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendees are willing to move into the multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favor of traders: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is disgraceful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector they would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about closures, decided to run away with the signing of a protocol between the City and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-room cinemas both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules foreseen are tax relief measures in favor of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like", observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counteract the overpowering power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many emotions shared, not to see the billboards blackened by dust I turn to the other side.
Links between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was available to align the choices of the Municipality to the interests of the Piromalli Cossa."
The charges are heavy that the magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria address to the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and to the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in a mafia association.
In handcuffs also Gioacchino Piromalli, the elderly mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his nephew lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of association for mafia delinquents, condemned to compensate 10 million euros.
"In disregard of any legal and moral norms, as well as common sense," the prosecutors write, the two local administrations had expressed a willingness to pay advice to lawyer Piromalli.
"It would have been granted to the cossa - write the judges - to enter officially within the municipalities facilitating the already huge possibilities of control and address of the public administration."
The president of the Calabrian regional junta Agazio Loiero does not hide that "collusions between local authorities and organized underworld there are several" in his region: "There are areas where the intensity of the mafia is stronger than in others, where collusion is almost inevitable.
But there are so many local politicians who resist the pressures of the 'ndrangheta, heroes who keep themselves clean."
The arrests this morning follow those of last July with which the police announced that they had beheaded the Piromalli cossa.
Since the end of April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro was dissolved but already in 1991, and always due to alleged conditioning between organized crime and local administration, local politicians had been relieved from the task of administering the Municipality.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, mayor of the UDC at the time of the dissolution, had been elected as the head of a center-right coalition, after the May 2006 ballot.
He shouted the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He called in the case the then Deputy Minister of the Interior Marco Minniti, accusing him of having planned everything for a political issue, but the judges, in the arrest order signed this morning, explain that the Piromalli cossa had even come to ask for the variation of the A3 project.
From the ordered environmental interceptions against Dal Torrione, the prosecutors write, emerged "the willingness to marry the needs of an entrepreneur, representative of a larger group notoriously close to the Piromalli, uniforming the choices of the public administration to the interests of the cosca".
When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones now come down in the field.
It is an endless field, occupying more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewables they’ve set their sights on, and now they’re trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of deriving energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, coinciding with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalists and the new increase in oil give momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by swelling plants.
This amount would be twice that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy and have always been committed to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesperson for a subsidiary of the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a good sign, especially considering that the U.S. continues to extract oil in Alaska and President Bush recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are taking the path of energy coming from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now plants like the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems to the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which makes the buoys move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants under design, awaiting only federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others bordering the coasts, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and planned investments up to $35 million for 2009.
